[
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277473\">Morgan Rogers</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/231815-monoids/topic/Favourites/near/192900387\" title=\"#narrow/stream/231815-monoids/topic/Favourites/near/192900387\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281583\">James Wood</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/231815-monoids/topic/Favourites/near/192899727\" title=\"#narrow/stream/231815-monoids/topic/Favourites/near/192899727\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think some good motivating examples of semirings are the tropical semirings, where the addition is a meet and the multiplication is an addition.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So you can construct a tropical semiring from any ordered monoid? If so, I hadn't thought about that before!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'm not sure where you get distributivity from, but it's believable that any semilattice which is compatibly a monoid forms a semiring. I'll have to check it.</p>",
        "id": 192901192,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1585996220
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Having thought about it, no, I don't think it's possible to get distributivity from anywhere other than just requiring it.</p>",
        "id": 192901441,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1585996659
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's no way to get ⊤ + x ≥ ⊤, for example. It could be that all sums are smaller than ⊤, or something.</p>",
        "id": 192901498,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1585996747
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>General monoids and semilattices can get pretty wild, I suppose.</p>",
        "id": 192901504,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1585996773
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281583\">James Wood</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/231815-monoids/topic/Favourites/near/192901192\" title=\"#narrow/stream/231815-monoids/topic/Favourites/near/192901192\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I'm not sure where you get distributivity from, but it's believable that any semilattice which is compatibly a monoid forms a semiring. I'll have to check it.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Isn't distributivity that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>∧</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∧</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a + (x \\wedge y) = (a + x) \\wedge (a + y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∧</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∧</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>? To be an ordered monoid, you want the addition to be order-preserving (on each side, for non-commutativity), so if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b \\leq x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83041em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span></span></span></span> we have <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a+b \\leq a+x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83041em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span></span></span></span> and similarly for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span>, so distributivity holds by the universal property of meets <span aria-label=\"+1\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f44d\" role=\"img\" title=\"+1\">:+1:</span> .</p>",
        "id": 192902981,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1585999144
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By “distributivity”, I also mean annihilation, which I'm not quite seeing (as I said above).</p>",
        "id": 192903133,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1585999370
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also, how do you get (a + x) ∧ (a + y) ≤ a + (x ∧ y)? It's not immediately obvious to me.</p>",
        "id": 192903211,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1585999541
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(this is also the binary version of what I was stumped on before)</p>",
        "id": 192903256,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1585999579
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah good point, I've only proved the other inequality. Oops!</p>",
        "id": 192903434,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1585999930
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So you could construct a pathological counterexample as soon as the monoid isn't totally ordered <span aria-label=\"smiley\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f603\" role=\"img\" title=\"smiley\">:smiley:</span></p>",
        "id": 192903538,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586000152
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Imagine a Y constructed as follows: Take three copies of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mo>+</mo></msub><mo>∪</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R_+ \\cup \\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.891661em;vertical-align:-0.208331em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.25833100000000003em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.00773em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">+</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.208331em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>, pointing upwards, and glue the zeros of two of them together strictly above the infinity of the third. I think one could come up with an addition on that which preserves the order but violates the other inequality? (just being lazy here by not coming up with it myself...)</p>",
        "id": 192903857,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586000702
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Even ℤ/2 might be a counterexample, now I think of it.</p>",
        "id": 192904695,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586002060
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah. Take {0≤1}, with 1 + 1 = 0. Then 1 + (1 ∧ 0) = 1 + 1 = 0, but (1 + 1) ∧ (1 + 0) = 0 ∧ 1 = 1.</p>",
        "id": 192904814,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586002212
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Wait, no, that's not monotonic, sorry.</p>",
        "id": 192904823,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586002245
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281583\">James Wood</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/231815-monoids/topic/Favourites/near/192904823\" title=\"#narrow/stream/231815-monoids/topic/Favourites/near/192904823\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Wait, no, that's not monotonic, sorry.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If it's totally ordered then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>∧</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\wedge y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.55556em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∧</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> is just <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span></span></span></span> or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> and since addition is required to be monotonic you get the reverse inequality for free</p>",
        "id": 192904884,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586002343
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Aah, yeah, that makes sense.</p>",
        "id": 192904910,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586002390
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And that makes up an interesting result.</p>",
        "id": 192904918,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586002404
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Though, do we need something more to get a + ⊤ = ⊤?</p>",
        "id": 192904973,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586002506
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I still don't see where that axiom comes from haha</p>",
        "id": 192905164,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586002835
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(ie why you expect/want it to hold)</p>",
        "id": 192905179,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586002862
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is a × 0 = 0.</p>",
        "id": 192905197,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586002912
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right, but I would take that as a theorem in ring theory, not one of the axioms, and I can't see a way that I would prove it there without additive inverses</p>",
        "id": 192905385,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586003166
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(not that I've looked very hard, mind you)</p>",
        "id": 192905407,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586003227
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it's only not one of the axioms of a ring because it happens to be a theorem of the others. But what you really want to say is that “a × any finite sum is a finite sum of a × each element”.</p>",
        "id": 192905413,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586003258
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Related nLab concept: <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/biased+definition\" title=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/biased+definition\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/biased+definition</a></p>",
        "id": 192905460,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586003324
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is one of the classic “peeling away inverses” moves.</p>",
        "id": 192905480,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586003391
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Consider the three element commutative monoid <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">⊥</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">⊤</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bot &lt; x &lt; \\top</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.73354em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⊥</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⊤</span></span></span></span> with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">⊥</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">⊤</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bot + x = x = \\top +x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⊥</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⊤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span></span></span></span>. It's trivially monotone and totally ordered but fails to have the property you're asking for, so the answer is no. <span aria-label=\"oh no\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f615\" role=\"img\" title=\"oh no\">:oh_no:</span></p>",
        "id": 192906435,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586004993
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does this counterexample even need the ⊥?</p>",
        "id": 192906776,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586005571
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess not, thinking about it. In fact, one can always just take addition and meet to coincide, since meet is idempotent and commutative, in order to demonstrate a counterexample!</p>",
        "id": 192906870,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586005751
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It reminds me of some conditions I've thought of requiring before: “everything bigger than 0 is itself 0” and “everything bigger than a sum is itself a sum of bigger summands”.</p>",
        "id": 192906932,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586005846
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>∀x. 0 ≤ x → 0 = x<br>\n∀x y z. x + y ≤ z → ∃x′ y′. x ≤ x′ &amp; y ≤ y′ &amp; x′ + y′ = z</p>",
        "id": 192907006,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1586005974
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This rekindles my curiosity about what internal monoids in a localic topos can look like.</p>",
        "id": 192907487,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586006717
    }
]